                    <body>
                              <pb n="1"/>
                              <p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Kingston, Jamaica</placeName>
                                        <date>14<hi rend="sup">th</hi> November 5610</date>.</p>
                              <p><addressee>Revd. Isaac Leeser</addressee>,</p>
                              <p rend="indent(2)">My dear Sir,</p>
                              <p rend="indent(4)">I avail myself of the present favorable<lb/>
                                        opportunity of replying to your welcome communication
                                                  <persName>Dr Glamorgan</persName>,<lb/> and also
                                        of acknowledging the receipt of a Parcel containing<lb/>
                                        Four sets of the present volume of the “Occident” to the
                                                  <date>October</date> No,<lb/> less one copy of No
                                        4. I have duly delivered them to the Gentlemen,<lb/> on
                                        whom, thro a little delicacy, I have not yet called for
                                        the<lb/> amount of subscription, but I intend doing so next
                                        week, and<lb/> handing over the same to <persName>Mr A C
                                                  Peixotto</persName>, your agent in this<lb/>
                                        <placeName>Island</placeName>.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(4)">Permit me to reiterate the high<lb/> sense I
                                        entertain of your kindness and friendly feeling in
                                        furnishing<lb/> me with the information requested of
                                        vacancies in congregations<lb/> in the <placeName>United
                                                  States</placeName>, requiring Hazanim. On mature
                                        reflection, it<lb/> is quite evident to me, that great
                                        (perhaps insurmountable)<lb/> difficulties must necessarily
                                        arise, in the endeavor to obtain a<lb/> situation in
                                                  <placeName>America</placeName>, unless the
                                        applicant be on the spot; to<lb/> give satisfactory proofs
                                        of his capability &amp;c. Notwithstanding<lb/> the
                                        confidence I entertain, that I would stand a <hi
                                                  rend="underline">very fair</hi><lb/> chance of
                                        gaining the approval of any respectable <add>קהלה</add> and
                                        that<lb/> the documentary recommendations which I could
                                        bring in testimony<lb/> of competency, position, and
                                        character, would be such as any<lb/> individual would be
                                        proud of possessing, still I must freely<lb/> admit, that it
                                        would be nevertheless advisable, if I could present<lb/>
                                        myself to the congregation amongst whom I desire to
                                        dwell,<lb/> and then and there afford them the means of
                                        judging for themselves<lb/>
                                        <hi rend="underline">at present</hi> I cannot do this. My
                                        engagements in <placeName>Jamaica</placeName> will<lb/> not
                                        be at an end till the <date>1<hi rend="sup">st</hi>
                                                  May</date> next. When that period<lb/> arrives, I
                                        will then be in a position to solicit your friendship<lb/>
                                        substantially, as (with God's Blessing) the opportunity may
                                        be<lb/> afforded me of a personal acquaintance with
                                        yourself, and other<lb/> Gentlemen interested in Jewish
                                        Affairs.</p>
                              <pb n="2"/>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">Thro the kind instruction of <persName>Hazan<lb/>
                                                  Lopez</persName>, I have made astonishing progress
                                        in the Portuguese minhag, and I was thereby enabled to
                                        officiate during the Holidays in a<lb/> manner perfectly
                                        surprising to myself in having so successfully<lb/> overcome
                                        the accent &amp;c of the German form of Reading. I
                                        entreat<lb/> you not to think me egotistical, or guilty of
                                        self adulation;—<lb/> I speak as I feel, and would, as
                                        freely admit, the faulty, just<lb/> as much as the
                                        successful performance of my duties. In<lb/> testimony of
                                        the satisfaction which I have given to the members<lb/> of
                                        the congregation who are under my spiritual guidance,
                                        the<lb/> enclosed letter was forwarded me, which (if you
                                        think it may be<lb/> serviceable to me) I request you will
                                        publish in the “Occident.”<lb/> According to your desire, I
                                        also transmit a short sermon, as<lb/> well as the Inaugural
                                        Address I delivered on my assumption<lb/> of office. Should
                                        it be your wish, I will feel much pleasure<lb/> to
                                        contribute now and then to the pages of your excellent
                                        periodical.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">I will not lose sight of your<lb/> request, in
                                        using my humble endeavors to obtain subscribers to the<lb/>
                                        Occident. Be assured, that in <hi rend="underline"
                                                  >anything</hi> that can be of benefit<lb/> to you,
                                        you may freely and readily command my zealous services.<lb/>
                                        If I fail of success, it shall not be thro the want of the
                                        will of<lb/> serving you.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)"><persName>Rabbi Jechiel Cohen</persName> quitted this<lb/>
                                        <placeName>Island</placeName> last week for <placeName>St
                                                  Thomas's</placeName>. He came here at a very<lb/>
                                        unfortunate period as regards the pecuniary position of
                                        the<lb/> community. He has collected about $350 in
                                                  <placeName>Kingston</placeName> and<lb/>
                                        <placeName>Spanish Town</placeName>, of which nearly $150
                                        were <del>coll</del> received from<lb/> the small
                                        congregation of the latter town. He has however<lb/> been
                                        paid marked respect and attention by all classes; and<lb/>
                                        (I believe) has lived here since his arrival without any
                                        expense<lb/> whatsoever. I introduced him to the chief
                                        members of the<lb/> congregation in <placeName>Spanish
                                                  Town</placeName>, and used some effort in
                                        forwarding<lb/> the objects of his mission. <persName>Rabbi
                                                  Nissim ben Shelomo</persName> is still<lb/> here,
                                        tho hitherto unsuccessful in his endeavors to collect
                                        money.<lb/> It may be uncharitable to form the opinion, but
                                        I do not</p>
                              <pb n="3"/>
                              <p>think the solution of a messenger like him has been
                                        <add>?</add>,<lb/> as he is quite unacquainted with the
                                        English language, manners,<lb/> or customs. Some effort is
                                        about being made in by behalf.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">My father returns you his thanks for<lb/> your
                                        remembrance and desires me to present his kind regards to
                                        you.<lb/> With the renewed assurance of my good wishes,</p>
                              <p rend="indent(6)">Believe me</p>
                              <p rend="indent(8)">My dear Sir</p>
                              <p rend="indent(9)">Yours very truly</p>
                              <p rend="indent(10)">
                                        <persName role="author">Henry S. Jacobs</persName>
                              </p>
                              <pb n="4"/>
                              <p>
                                        <addressee>Reverend Isaac Leeser</addressee>
                              </p>
